Today we celebrated your life and said our goodbyes. It was hard. Beyond emotional. But the love in the room was palpable. You touched so many lives and it was very clear to see that today. 

Losing a parent is hard and knowing that we have to do this four times over in our life is unbearable. But this is the way it’s supposed to be right? We, the children, must endure the pain of burying/cremating our parents. Hopefully when they’re old and gray. It’s not supposed to be the other way around. No parent wants that. That’s what’s gotten me through this. That it’s the cycle of life. I pray that my own children will one day endure the same pain and continue the pattern of life and death the way we all hope and wish for it to be. 

We are going to do our best to remember him the way he was before he got sick. Remember the joy, laughter, stories and adventures. Remember who he was in his youth and prime. Not who he was in the end. 

To all of you— we are so grateful for you. Your messages have been full of the love and hope that we need right now. Thank you thank you thank you 🙏🏽

Biggest Disney on a Budget tip: You don’t have to stay at the resort. TBH- we were barely in the room and only went there to sleep so I opted for Hampton Inn Orlando/Buena Vista. The rooms were remarkably affordable and there was free breakfast. I choose not to stay at places without free breakfast because ordering food in the AM for a family four is such a thing. 

The hotel we stayed at offered a shuttle service to the park but it wasn’t convenient in terms of timing so we used @uber. In Disney area, Uber has an option to get an Uber with a car seat. We took our own inflatable boosters, which I’ll link in my bio because I highly recommend these for all travel with booster aged kids. 

Also— all the Disney resorts are very accessible. Meaning— even if you’re not staying there, you can hang out there 😜 🤫 the monorails are all free as are the ferries etc so we were glad we needed up saving on the hotel.

This is our 10th Valentine’s Day together, and each one just gets better and better.

On our first Valentine’s Day, you brought me flowers and took me to watch my first ever New York Broadway musical, Aladdin. You didn’t even like the theater, but you opened yourself to trying it just for me and found that it’s not so bad. We also got into a huge fight that night right before we left to the city. Grunting and yelling under our breath in our tiny attic of a house apartment with the green carpet and yellow walls. It’s crazy how the way we used to fight then is so vastly different from how we fight now. We used to fight like strangers who didn’t have the same goal in mind, a resolution, and now we fight like family, knowing that, even if we’re mad that we still love each other, and we’ll still find ways to show it to each other throughout the argument.

Every year it got better. We got better. Every Valentine’s Day, you have, without fail, made me feel special. I hope I made you feel special, but I just feel like you do it so much better. Things and flowers aside, the best gift you give me every year is just being by my side, without judgment, and with full support for all my crazy ideas. #baby3

I look back at the last 10 years, and I see how every year we have continued to grow together. We’re growing in the same direction, at a similar pace while giving each other grace and allowing each other to be human. It’s such a beautiful thing.

You are not the man I married. The man I married, was great. But you sir are phenomenal. Exquisite. Beyond words. You, today, are far better than that man. I know you feel the same way about me too and I love that about us. Were able to recognize our own mistakes, places we can improve, and push each other towards being better people every, single day. Thank you for that.

I got so many DM’s yesterday about my morning routine and the kids morning routines after I shared that they do Kumon first thing in the morning. So I filmed my morning today. Every time we are at this stage of life, we learn something new. No two pregnancies are alike and neither are the experiences with those babies. I have spent the better part of the last 5 years building this community. I started sharing on here in January of 2018 when I was 16 weeks pregnant with Kareena and continued through “unprecedented times” with 2 under 2.

This journey.

This mama is choosing to intentionally slow down on all fronts 🙃 but I’ll be here, sharing life as usual, because being here, chatting with all of you and sharing my journey, is truly what brings me so much joy. ❤️

A little over 6 years ago, days before Krish came into the world, I had a feeling in the pit of my stomach that everything was not okay. I sat with that feeling that turned into anxiety for days, waiting for my upcoming appointment & when it still stayed persistent even after my 37 week doctor’s appointment, I went with my gut, which ended up saving Krish’s life.

Last week, the same feeling came back. At 37 weeks pregnant. Just like that first time. Paralyzing anxiety that was shouting that Keshav was not okay. I told myself it was a trauma response. I told myself it was irrational fear and anxiety of what could be. I tried to reason with myself because there’s no way I could “just know” twice, right? 

I expressed my anxieties to 🐰 in the texts above and he supported me to go and get it checked out. 

So after school pick up, I went to the hospital to mostly ease my anxiety. They did an NST to monitor his heart rate. Everything was looking pretty good until I had a solid contraction and his heart rate decelerated. They decided to monitor me for another hour and saw that I was continuing to have contractions that were 10 minutes apart and getting stronger, a pattern that suggested I might be in actual labor. When his heart rate decelerated again after my cervical exam, this time worse than the first, they immediately prepped me for surgery. 

Here’s the thing, Keshav passed his bio physical exam. His fluids were fine. He looked good on the ultrasound, but for some reason, most likely my placenta and history of inter-uterine growth restriction with Krish, he wasn’t thriving.

My gut feeling was right. Again. He needed to get out and although the urgency level wasn’t to the level of Krish where if I waited a day longer, I’d be telling a diff story, I’ll be forever grateful that 🐰 texted me the reassurance I needed to trust my mama gut cuz it’s true—- mama always knows! 

Thanking the universe every moment I can 🙏🏽

I woke up in a mood today because I feel like my body is in limbo. I can’t really work out as hard as I want because I’m still healing and I don’t wanna bust my wound open after finally getting it closed.  I can’t really count my calories or anything because I need to make breastmilk. Most days, I’m super confident in my post partum skin. I’m proud of my body and everything that it’s created. I also know that I need to respect my body and give it time to heal, but today I struggled. 

Nothing looked right, nothing fit right, nothing made me feel good.  I felt like a foreigner in my own body because I didn’t know how to dress it. I was uncomfortable in everything I put on, and it almost made me not want to go. 

Making this video and watching it helped me realize that I don’t look so bad. I definitely don’t look as bad as I feel. The clothes actually look okay on me.  Well, the ones that fit.

This is just a reminder to myself that I need to be patient. I need to let my body do what it needs to do to be where it needs to be. There are chances that even if I work my butt off, I’ll never be a size 2 again, and if that’s the case, then, so be it. But once I know that, I can replenish my closet with clothes that fit me. Right now I’m hanging onto all my clothes because I don’t know where my body is going to end up and I don’t know what’s going to fit in six months, but just looking at them sitting there gives me so much anxiety

So I think what I’m going to do is box away all the clothes that don’t fit and only keep out the clothes that do. By doing this, I’m allowing myself explore only the options that actually fit me so I don’t have to go through the whole trying on process and the emotions that come with it every time I go out. I want to love my body in every state that it’s in because it deserves that. I deserve that. So that’s what I’m going to keep trying to do.

Poppin’ different kinds of bottles these days.

When traditional media shows you an alcoholic, it tends to only show you one type. One version of rock bottom that we’ve come to correlate with the term alcoholic. But here I am, deep in my addiction and I looked happy, healthy and in control. But I was struggling internally with addiction and dependency. I didn’t drink in the mornings. I didn’t drink every day. I didn’t even get drunk every time I drank, but I knew I had a problem. 

1001 days ago, I had my last sip of alcohol. I’ll be honest, the wine that night didn’t taste sweet anymore. It didn’t feel good. I knew that the alcohol was in control. I remember not even wanting that glass of wine and questioning why I was drinking it. My reasoning was that because I opened the bottle and didn’t want it to go to waste. But the real reason was that I was addicted to alcohol. I couldn’t say no anymore. 

My night caps only got stronger and stronger through the pandemic and I knew deep down that I had a problem, but I didn’t want to face it even though I knew I had to. I knew it would ruin me & I couldn’t do that to myself or my kids. 

So 1000 days ago, I made the decision to stop drinking. I wanted to do better, be better. I wanted to be the one controlling my life. I didn’t want to feel the way I felt. So I quit. And it was hard. The hardest thing I’ve ever done, but I’m forever grateful for how my life has unfolded since then. I built this community. I wrote a book (releases June 2024). I created my dream job as a content creator. And I’m just getting started.

These easy three ingredient truffles were such a hit at Friendsgiving this past weekend, and I know I’m gonna be making them for the rest of my life. 

Angie’s truffles (thank you @amathe11)

ingredients:
One large box of Oreos 
One block of cream cheese, or 8 ounces of whipped cream cheese 
Ghirardelli chocolate chips 
Sprinkles are optional 

Directions :
1. Turn the all Oreos into crumbs 
2. Mix in the cream cheese. This was much easier & quicker with an electric mixer. 
3. Roll into 1 inch balls. It doesn’t really matter what size it is just rolled into balls.
4. Put in the fridge for like an hour or two.
5. Melt the chocolate. Boiled water in a pot and put a bowl inside the pot, then put the chocolate inside the bowl so it’s not directly touching the hot pot that’s touching the stove. I’m sure there’s a name for this method of melting chocolate, but I don’t know what it is.
6. Use a fork to cover the balls and chocolate
7. Place in fridge for like another hour or two.
8. Enjoy!

Traveling with baby tips 👇🏽. 

Just finished up a solo trip to my cousin’s wedding with my 7 month old. It was fantastic so i thought I’d share some tips for you if you’re traveling alone with your baby or babies

- Don’t be afraid to ask for help. Most airports, if not all have assistance for anyone requiring help and that includes parents that are traveling alone with children. You can go to the information desk and ask for assistance at any time. I have not used the service myself because I haven’t felt the need yet, but I’m glad to know that it’s there. I also asked for help from the people who are sitting next to me on the plane when I needed it as well as the air hostesses. Anytime I needed to use the restroom, the air hostesses were happy to hold the baby. 
- Take your time going through security. Some airports allow you to go through the wheelchair access line, so make sure to check if you can go through there before going through standard security. It’ll save you time and it’s a lot easier to get through.
- Take your baby carrier. This helps me have my hands-free to do other things like break down the stroller or lift my suitcase onto the belt, etc. even if the baby hates and cries in it, you’ll still have your hands free. 
- Don’t have expectations of how it will go. Sometimes Keshav does really well on the flight and other times I’m doing squats in the aisle trying to get him to go to sleep. it’s hit or miss and I never have any expectations so I’m never disappointed or frustrated. Go with the flow because you got this. 
-  don’t stress about what anyone else thinks if your baby is stressed or crying. Try to stay calm and focus on you and your baby and block out the noise. I have learned that most people are understanding and the ones who aren’t, I ignore them.

This was by the far the best all inclusive experience we have had in Mexico. We stayed at @velasvallarta in Puerto Vallarta for 3 nights and 4 days. We had the two bedroom family suite which was more than enough room for the 5 of us. 

I prefer this side of Mexico over Cancun, riviera maya etc for many reasons.
 🤌🏾Cleaner beaches (no kelp)
 🤌🏾Safer town if you want to leave the resort - we didn’t leave this time but we learned a lot about it and are going to definitely explore on our next trip 
 🤌🏾Less shady airport - no one was approaching us for rides on the way out and people were very helpful. Overall, we liked the whole airport better.
 🤌🏾The resort was only a ten minute drive from the airport which was awesome. 
 🤌🏾 @velasvallarta is an all suites resort and every balcony has a view of the ocean. 
 🤌🏾 the food and variety was awesome. I can’t speak for vegetarians because we didn’t eat a lot of vegetarian food even though the options were there. We loved dining at Ribera and the Indian restaurant (which is a seasonal pop up) was so dang good!!! 
 🤌🏾 I loved the aesthetics. It looked like a dream every day. 
 🤌🏾 the music at the main pool wasn’t overwhelming and there were two other pool areas to choose from. 
 🤌🏾 you can order food to the pool, which is something most resorts we have visited don’t do. Getting a plate of fries and fruit pool side is key on vacation!!

Friends! It’s holiday season and although this should be a given year round, please do not forget about your sober and pregnant friends! It’s so nice when we go to a party and there’s non alcoholic options beyond soda, juice and Topo Chico.

This spicy margarita will leave your guests impressed and honestly even the non sober friends will want you to make them one.

Ingredients:

2 oz. Ritual Tequila Alternative 1 oz. fresh lime juice 1 oz. triple sec ½ oz. agave nectar ½ jalapeño pepper Basil Leaf
Lime seltzer water (I used Waterloo) Tajin or Trader Joe’s chili and lime seasoning (for rim)

Pour Tequila Alternative over jalapeño and basil, sliced lengthwise, in a cocktail shaker. Let sit at room temperature for at least 15 minutes. The longer, the spicier. Add lime, triple sec, agave and ice. Shake shake shake. Pour over ice into your salt-rimmed glass. Top with lime seltzer water. Garnish with jalapeño slices and basil leaf.

*Drink adapted from @ritualzeroproof “heat wave”
